FabricMC Server Mod Analysis

Let's break down this mod systematically, starting with what it does, then how it accomplishes that.

What This Mod Does

This mod performs two tasks:

  1. Displays spawn coordinates to all players via action bar text every second (20 ticks)
  2. Removes Warden entities immediately when they attempt to spawn

Architecture Overview

FabricMC uses an event-driven architecture. Your mod registers listeners that execute when specific game events occur. No inheritance, no complex dependency injection - just callbacks.

Code Walkthrough

Class Declaration

java
public class Hud implements ModInitializer

ModInitializer is the Fabric entry point interface. When Fabric loads your mod, it looks for classes implementing this interface and calls their onInitialize() method.

Tick Counter

java
private int tickCounter = 0;

Minecraft runs at 20 ticks per second. This counter tracks ticks to create a 1-second interval. We increment it every tick and reset at 20.

Initialization Method

java
public void onInitialize()

This executes once when the server starts. All event registration happens here.

Server Tick Event

java
ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register(server -> {

This registers a callback that runs every tick, after the server finishes its tick processing. The lambda receives the MinecraftServer instance.

The logic inside:

  • Increment the counter
  • When counter hits 20 (1 second elapsed), reset it and iterate all online players
  • For each player, retrieve their world's spawn position
  • Send spawn coordinates to the player's action bar (that's the true parameter in displayClientMessage)

Entity Load Event

java
ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {

This callback fires whenever any entity loads into any world. Loading happens when:

  • An entity spawns naturally
  • An entity is summoned via command
  • A chunk loads containing a saved entity

The logic:

  • Check if the entity type is WARDEN
  • If yes, call discard() to immediately remove it
  • Log the prevention

Key Technical Details

Why ServerLevel casting?

java
ServerLevel level = (ServerLevel) player.level();

player.level() returns Level, but we need ServerLevel to access server-specific data like spawn information. This cast is safe because we're in a server-side mod.

Spawn Position Retrieval

java
BlockPos spawnPos = level.getLevelData().getRespawnData().pos();

This retrieves the world spawn, not individual player bed spawns. Every dimension has a world spawn point stored in the level data.

Action Bar vs Chat

The true parameter in displayClientMessage() sends text to the action bar (above the hotbar). false would send it to chat. Action bar messages don't clutter chat and get replaced each time.

Entity Discard

entity.discard() marks the entity for removal. It doesn't delete it instantly but queues it for removal in the next tick cleanup phase. For spawn prevention, this is effectively immediate.

Potential Issues

Spawn position might be null - getRespawnData().pos() could potentially return null in certain dimension configurations. Production code should null-check this.

All dimensions share logic - This displays spawn for whatever dimension the player is in. The Nether and End have spawn points too, which might not be what you expect.

Entity load fires frequently - This event triggers for every entity load, not just spawns. For performance-critical mods with many entities, you'd want to be careful here, but for Warden prevention this is fine since Wardens are rare.

Implementing a Directional Indicator to World Spawn

Mental Model: How Direction Works

Before we write code, let's build your understanding of the coordinate system and directional math.

Minecraft's Coordinate System

  • X axis: East (+) / West (-)
  • Y axis: Up (+) / Down (-)
  • Z axis: South (+) / North (-)

You're standing somewhere in this 3D space. The spawn is somewhere else. We need to calculate which direction to face to look at spawn.

The Math We Need

Given:

  • Your position: (playerX, playerZ) - we ignore Y for horizontal direction
  • Spawn position: (spawnX, spawnZ)

We calculate:

  • Delta X: spawnX - playerX (how far east/west)
  • Delta Z: spawnZ - playerZ (how far north/south)

Then we use atan2(deltaX, deltaZ) to get the angle in radians from north (0) going clockwise.

Player's Rotation

The player has a yRot value (yaw rotation) that tells us which direction they're facing:

  • 0 = South
  • 90 = West
  • 180 = North
  • 270 = East

Relative Angle

To point an arrow toward spawn on the player's screen, we need the angle relative to where they're looking, not absolute world direction.

relativeAngle = angleToSpawn - playerYaw

This tells us "turn X degrees left/right from where you're facing to look at spawn."

Character Selection

We'll use Unicode arrows. Good choices:

  • - Simple up arrow
  • - Bold up arrow
  • - Triangle

Problem: Minecraft's action bar doesn't support arbitrary rotation of characters. We can't actually rotate a single arrow.

Solution: Use 8 directional arrows and pick the closest one:

  • North (front)
  • Northeast
  • East (right)
  • Southeast
  • South (behind)
  • Southwest
  • West (left)
  • Northwest

Implementation: Step by Step

Let's modify your code. I'll show each change with explanation.

Step 1: Change tick interval from 20 to 5

java
if (tickCounter >= 5) {

This makes updates happen 4 times per second instead of once per second. More responsive but still efficient.

Step 2: Calculate angle to spawn

Inside your player loop, after getting spawn position, add:

java
double deltaX = spawnPos.getX() - player.getX();
double deltaZ = spawnPos.getZ() - player.getZ();
double angleToSpawn = Math.toDegrees(Math.atan2(deltaX, deltaZ));

Why atan2(deltaX, deltaZ) not atan2(deltaZ, deltaX)?

atan2(y, x) returns the angle from the positive X-axis. But in Minecraft's coordinate system, "forward" is the Z-axis. We want 0 to mean "facing positive Z" (south), so we swap the parameters.

Math.toDegrees() converts radians to degrees because we think in degrees.

Step 3: Get player's facing direction

java
float playerYaw = player.getYRot();

This returns the direction the player is facing in degrees.

Step 4: Calculate relative angle

java
double relativeAngle = angleToSpawn - playerYaw;

Now we have "how many degrees from my current facing do I need to turn to face spawn?"

Step 5: Normalize the angle to -180 to 180 range

java
while (relativeAngle > 180) relativeAngle -= 360;
while (relativeAngle < -180) relativeAngle += 360;

Why? Angles wrap around. 350 and -10 are the same direction. We want the angle in the range where 0 = straight ahead, positive = turn right, negative = turn left, and 180 = behind you.

Step 6: Map angle to directional arrow

java
String arrow = getDirectionalArrow(relativeAngle);

We'll write this function next. It takes the relative angle and returns the appropriate arrow character.

Step 7: Create the directional arrow function

Add this method to your class, outside of onInitialize():

java
private String getDirectionalArrow(double angle) {
    double normalizedAngle = ((angle % 360) + 360) % 360;
    
    if (normalizedAngle >= 337.5 || normalizedAngle < 22.5) return "";
    if (normalizedAngle >= 22.5 && normalizedAngle < 67.5) return "";
    if (normalizedAngle >= 67.5 && normalizedAngle < 112.5) return "";
    if (normalizedAngle >= 112.5 && normalizedAngle < 157.5) return "";
    if (normalizedAngle >= 157.5 && normalizedAngle < 202.5) return "";
    if (normalizedAngle >= 202.5 && normalizedAngle < 247.5) return "";
    if (normalizedAngle >= 247.5 && normalizedAngle < 292.5) return "";
    return "";
}

Breaking this down:

We divide the 360 circle into 8 segments of 45 each:

  • 0 (22.5) = straight ahead =
  • 45 (22.5) = ahead-right =
  • etc.

The normalization ((angle % 360) + 360) % 360 ensures the angle is 0-360, handling negative inputs correctly.

Step 8: Update the display message

java
String message = String.format("%s Spawn: X=%d Y=%d Z=%d", 
        arrow,
        spawnPos.getX(),
        spawnPos.getY(),
        spawnPos.getZ());

Complete Modified Code

Here's your full updated onInitialize() method:

java
@Override
public void onInitialize() {
    LOGGER.info("HUD mod initializing...");

    ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register(server -> {
        tickCounter++;
        if (tickCounter >= 5) {
            tickCounter = 0;
            for (ServerPlayer player : server.getPlayerList().getPlayers()) {
                ServerLevel level = (ServerLevel) player.level();
                BlockPos spawnPos = level.getLevelData().getRespawnData().pos();

                double deltaX = spawnPos.getX() - player.getX();
                double deltaZ = spawnPos.getZ() - player.getZ();
                double angleToSpawn = Math.toDegrees(Math.atan2(deltaX, deltaZ));
                
                float playerYaw = player.getYRot();
                double relativeAngle = angleToSpawn - playerYaw;
                
                while (relativeAngle > 180) relativeAngle -= 360;
                while (relativeAngle < -180) relativeAngle += 360;
                
                String arrow = getDirectionalArrow(relativeAngle);

                String message = String.format("%s Spawn: X=%d Y=%d Z=%d", 
                        arrow,
                        spawnPos.getX(),
                        spawnPos.getY(),
                        spawnPos.getZ());
                player.displayClientMessage(Component.literal(message), true);
            }
        }
    });

    ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {
        if (entity.getType() == EntityType.WARDEN) {
            entity.discard();
            LOGGER.info("Prevented warden spawn at {}", entity.blockPosition());
        }
    });

    LOGGER.info("HUD mod initialized!");
}

Performance Considerations

Why is 5 ticks efficient?

  • Runs 4 times per second
  • Only loops through online players (typically small number)
  • Math operations are trivial (a few multiplications, one atan2)
  • String formatting is cheap
  • No world queries, no entity searches

Cost per tick:
Players (1 position read + 4 arithmetic ops + 1 atan2 + 1 string format + 1 network packet)

For 20 players at 5-tick intervals: ~80 operations per second. Negligible.

Adding Distance-Based Circle Indicators

The Logic

  • Distance < 1 block: (standing on spawn)
  • Distance < 5 blocks: (very close)
  • Distance >= 5 blocks: directional arrow

Code Placement

Put this right after you calculate relativeAngle normalization and before getDirectionalArrow() call.

Here's the section with context:

java
float playerYaw = player.getYRot();
double relativeAngle = angleToSpawn - playerYaw;

while (relativeAngle > 180) relativeAngle -= 360;
while (relativeAngle < -180) relativeAngle += 360;

double distanceToSpawn = Math.sqrt(deltaX * deltaX + deltaZ * deltaZ);

String arrow;
if (distanceToSpawn < 1.0) {
    arrow = "";
} else if (distanceToSpawn < 5.0) {
    arrow = "";
} else {
    arrow = getDirectionalArrow(relativeAngle);
}

String message = String.format("%s Spawn: X=%d Y=%d Z=%d",

Why This Order?

We already calculated deltaX and deltaZ for the angle. Now we reuse them for distance using the Pythagorean theorem: sqrt(x + z).

We check distance first because if you're standing on spawn, showing an arrow would be pointless. The checks cascade from most specific (on spawn) to most general (show direction).

The Distance Calculation

Math.sqrt(deltaX * deltaX + deltaZ * deltaZ) gives you straight-line horizontal distance ignoring Y-axis. If you want true 3D distance including vertical:

java
double deltaY = spawnPos.getY() - player.getY();
double distanceToSpawn = Math.sqrt(deltaX * deltaX + deltaY * deltaY + deltaZ * deltaZ);

But horizontal-only makes more sense here since spawn is a point on the ground.

Your angle normalization has a typo:

java

Should be:

java
while (relativeAngle < -180)

You're missing the negative sign. This causes the angle to never normalize correctly into the -180 to 180 range.

Mental Model: Commands and Persistent Data

Understanding Commands in Fabric

Commands in Minecraft use Brigadier, a command framework from Mojang. The mental model:

  1. Register command nodes (literal text, arguments)
  2. Define execution logic
  3. Commands run server-side, have access to player context

Understanding Data Persistence

We need to store pins between server restarts. JSON file approach:

File location: world/data/pins.json

Structure:

json
{
  "spawn": {"x": 100, "y": 64, "z": -200},
  "swamp village": {"x": 450, "y": 70, "z": 300}
}

Operations needed:

  • Load JSON on server start
  • Save JSON when pins change
  • Check if "spawn" exists, create if missing

Implementation Plan

  1. Add Fabric command API dependency
  2. Create pin data structure
  3. Create JSON read/write functions
  4. Register /pin command
  5. Initialize spawn pin on server start

Let's build this step by step.

Step 1: Add Command API Registration

Add this import at the top:

java
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.command.v2.CommandRegistrationCallback;
import net.minecraft.commands.Commands;
import net.minecraft.commands.arguments.MessageArgument;
import com.mojang.brigadier.context.CommandContext;
import net.minecraft.commands.CommandSourceStack;
import com.google.gson.Gson;
import com.google.gson.GsonBuilder;
import com.google.gson.reflect.TypeToken;
import java.io.*;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Path;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

Step 2: Add Class Fields

Add these fields to your Hud class, right after tickCounter:

java
private static final Gson GSON = new GsonBuilder().setPrettyPrinting().create();
private static final String PINS_FILE = "data/pins.json";
private Map<String, PinLocation> pins = new HashMap<>();

Step 3: Create Pin Data Structure

Add this nested class inside your Hud class, after the fields:

java
private static class PinLocation {
    public final int x;
    public final int y;
    public final int z;

    public PinLocation(int x, int y, int z) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
        this.z = z;
    }
}

Why this structure? Simple data holder. No getters, no setters. Gson serializes public fields directly to JSON.

Step 4: Create Save Function

Add this method to your class:

java
private void savePins() {
    try {
        Path dataDir = Path.of("data");
        if (!Files.exists(dataDir)) {
            Files.createDirectories(dataDir);
        }
        
        try (FileWriter writer = new FileWriter(PINS_FILE)) {
            GSON.toJson(pins, writer);
        }
        
        LOGGER.info("Saved {} pins to {}", pins.size(), PINS_FILE);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        LOGGER.error("Failed to save pins", e);
    }
}

How this works:

  • Check if data/ directory exists, create if not
  • Open file writer
  • Gson converts Map<String, PinLocation> to JSON
  • Auto-closes writer with try-with-resources

Step 5: Create Load Function

java
private void loadPins() {
    File file = new File(PINS_FILE);
    if (!file.exists()) {
        LOGGER.info("No pins file found, starting fresh");
        return;
    }
    
    try (FileReader reader = new FileReader(file)) {
        TypeToken<Map<String, PinLocation>> typeToken = new TypeToken<>() {};
        pins = GSON.fromJson(reader, typeToken.getType());
        if (pins == null) {
            pins = new HashMap<>();
        }
        LOGGER.info("Loaded {} pins from {}", pins.size(), PINS_FILE);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        LOGGER.error("Failed to load pins", e);
        pins = new HashMap<>();
    }
}

TypeToken explained: Gson needs to know the generic type Map<String, PinLocation> at runtime. Java erases generics, so we use TypeToken to preserve the type information.

Step 6: Initialize Spawn Pin

Add this method:

java
private void ensureSpawnPin(ServerLevel level) {
    if (!pins.containsKey("spawn")) {
        BlockPos spawnPos = level.getLevelData().getRespawnData().pos();
        pins.put("spawn", new PinLocation(spawnPos.getX(), spawnPos.getY(), spawnPos.getZ()));
        savePins();
        LOGGER.info("Created spawn pin at {}", spawnPos);
    }
}

Step 7: Register the Command

Add this inside onInitialize(), right after the LOGGER.info("HUD mod initializing..."); line:

java
loadPins();

CommandRegistrationCallback.EVENT.register((dispatcher, registryAccess, environment) -> {
    dispatcher.register(
        Commands.literal("pin")
            .then(Commands.argument("name", MessageArgument.message())
                .executes(this::executePin))
    );
});

Breaking this down:

Commands.literal("pin") - The command starts with literal text "/pin"

Commands.argument("name", MessageArgument.message()) - After "/pin", accept an argument called "name" that captures everything after as a message (this handles spaces without quotes)

.executes(this::executePin) - When command runs, call executePin method

Why MessageArgument? It captures the entire remaining text as one argument. "/pin swamp village" captures "swamp village" as a single name. No quotes needed.

Step 8: Create Command Execution Logic

Add this method:

java
private int executePin(CommandContext<CommandSourceStack> context) {
    try {
        ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
        String pinName = MessageArgument.getMessage(context, "name").getString();
        
        int x = (int) player.getX();
        int y = (int) player.getY();
        int z = (int) player.getZ();
        
        pins.put(pinName, new PinLocation(x, y, z));
        savePins();
        
        player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
            String.format("aPin '%s' created at X:%d Y:%d H:%d", pinName, x, z, y)
        ));
        
        return 1;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        LOGGER.error("Error executing pin command", e);
        return 0;
    }
}

How commands work:

Return value: 1 = success, 0 = failure. Affects command block behavior and /execute conditionals.

context.getSource() - Gets who/what ran the command

getPlayerOrException() - Ensures a player ran it (not console or command block)

MessageArgument.getMessage() - Retrieves the "name" argument we defined

sendSystemMessage() - Sends feedback to player (chat message)

a - Minecraft color code for green

Step 9: Call ensureSpawnPin on Server Start

Inside your existing ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register callback, add this right at the start of the lambda, before tickCounter++:

java
ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register(server -> {
    if (tickCounter == 0 && !server.getPlayerList().getPlayers().isEmpty()) {
        ServerPlayer firstPlayer = server.getPlayerList().getPlayers().get(0);
        ensureSpawnPin(firstPlayer.level());
    }
    
    tickCounter++;

Why this approach? We wait for at least one player to be online so we can access their level to get spawn coordinates. We only check when tickCounter == 0 to run this once at the start.

                    arrow = getDirectionalArrow(relativeAngle);
                }

                String message = String.format("%s X: %d Y: %d H: %d",
                        arrow,
                        spawnPos.getX(),
                        spawnPos.getZ(),
                        spawnPos.getY());

                player.displayClientMessage(Component.literal(message), true);
            }
        }
    });

    ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {
        if (entity.getType() == EntityType.WARDEN) {
            entity.discard();
            LOGGER.info("Prevented warden spawn at {}", entity.blockPosition());
        }
    });

    LOGGER.info("HUD mod initialized!");
}

Excellent Question: Dimension Awareness

This is a real design decision. Let's think through the use cases.

Current Implementation Issue

Right now, all players share one global pins.json file. Problems:

  1. Player A creates "base" at coords (100, 64, 200)
  2. Player B creates "base" at coords (500, 70, -300)
  3. Result: Player B overwrites Player A's pin

Also, no dimension tracking. If you pin "nether fortress" in the Nether, then look for it in the Overworld, you'll be navigating to coordinates that exist in a different dimension.

What We Actually Need

Separate pins per player, with dimension tracking for each pin.

Mental Model: Three Approaches

Option 1: Per-player files with dimensions 

data/pins/player-uuid.json
json
{
  "base": {"x": 100, "y": 64, "z": 200, "dimension": "minecraft:overworld"},
  "nether fortress": {"x": 50, "y": 80, "z": 25, "dimension": "minecraft:the_nether"}
}
```

**Option 2: Single file, nested by player and dimension**
```
data/pins.json
json
{
  "uuid-1234": {
    "minecraft:overworld": {
      "base": {"x": 100, "y": 64, "z": 200}
    },
    "minecraft:the_nether": {
      "nether fortress": {"x": 50, "y": 80, "z": 25}
    }
  }
}

Option 3: Per-player files, dimension stored per pin (RECOMMENDED)

Same as Option 1. Simpler to work with, cleaner separation.

Why Dimension Matters

Player creates "portal" in Overworld at (800, 70, 800). The corresponding Nether coordinates are (100, 70, 100). Without dimension tracking:

  • Player in Nether tries to navigate to "portal"
  • Sees arrow pointing to (800, 800)
  • That's way off in the Nether
  • Confusion

The Right Solution

Store dimension with each pin. When displaying arrow, only show it if player is in the same dimension as the pin. Otherwise show a different indicator like (cross circle) or message like "Different dimension".

Updated Implementation

Step 1: Update PinLocation class

java
private static class PinLocation {
    public final int x;
    public final int y;
    public final int z;
    public final String dimension;

    public PinLocation(int x, int y, int z, String dimension) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
        this.z = z;
        this.dimension = dimension;
    }
}

Step 2: Update class fields

Replace:

java

With:

Why? Outer map: player UUID Inner map: pin name pin location

Step 3: Update save function

java
private void savePins(String playerUuid) {
    try {
        Path dataDir = Path.of("data/pins");
        if (!Files.exists(dataDir)) {
            Files.createDirectories(dataDir);
        }
        
        String filename = String.format("data/pins/%s.json", playerUuid);
        try (FileWriter writer = new FileWriter(filename)) {
            GSON.toJson(playerPins.get(playerUuid), writer);
        }
        
        LOGGER.info("Saved pins for player {}", playerUuid);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        LOGGER.error("Failed to save pins for player {}", playerUuid, e);
    }
}

Step 4: Update load function

java
private void loadPins(String playerUuid) {
    String filename = String.format("data/pins/%s.json", playerUuid);
    File file = new File(filename);
    
    if (!file.exists()) {
        playerPins.put(playerUuid, new HashMap<>());
        LOGGER.info("No pins file for player {}, starting fresh", playerUuid);
        return;
    }
    
    try (FileReader reader = new FileReader(file)) {
        TypeToken<Map<String, PinLocation>> typeToken = new TypeToken<>() {};
        Map<String, PinLocation> pins = GSON.fromJson(reader, typeToken.getType());
        if (pins == null) {
            pins = new HashMap<>();
        }
        playerPins.put(playerUuid, pins);
        LOGGER.info("Loaded {} pins for player {}", pins.size(), playerUuid);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        LOGGER.error("Failed to load pins for player {}", playerUuid, e);
        playerPins.put(playerUuid, new HashMap<>());
    }
}

Step 5: Update ensureSpawnPin

java
private void ensureSpawnPin(ServerPlayer player) {
    String uuid = player.getStringUUID();
    
    if (!playerPins.containsKey(uuid)) {
        loadPins(uuid);
    }
    
    Map<String, PinLocation> pins = playerPins.get(uuid);
    
    if (!pins.containsKey("spawn")) {
        ServerLevel level = player.level();
        BlockPos spawnPos = level.getLevelData().getRespawnData().pos();
        String dimension = level.dimension().location().toString();
        
        pins.put("spawn", new PinLocation(
            spawnPos.getX(), 
            spawnPos.getY(), 
            spawnPos.getZ(),
            dimension
        ));
        savePins(uuid);
        LOGGER.info("Created spawn pin for player {} at {}", uuid, spawnPos);
    }
}

Step 6: Update executePin command

java
private int executePin(CommandContext<CommandSourceStack> context) {
    try {
        ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
        String uuid = player.getStringUUID();
        String pinName = MessageArgument.getMessage(context, "name").getString();
        
        if (!playerPins.containsKey(uuid)) {
            loadPins(uuid);
        }
        
        int x = (int) player.getX();
        int y = (int) player.getY();
        int z = (int) player.getZ();
        String dimension = player.level().dimension().location().toString();
        
        playerPins.get(uuid).put(pinName, new PinLocation(x, y, z, dimension));
        savePins(uuid);
        
        player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
            String.format("aPin '%s' created at X:%d Y:%d H:%d [%s]", 
                pinName, x, z, y, dimension)
        ));
        
        return 1;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        LOGGER.error("Error executing pin command", e);
        return 0;
    }
}

Step 7: Remove global loadPins from onInitialize

Remove this line from the start of onInitialize():

java
loadPins();  // DELETE THIS

Why? We now load pins per-player on-demand when they first create a pin or join the server.

Step 8: Update ensureSpawnPin call in tick event

Change this part of the tick event:

java
if (tickCounter == 0 && !server.getPlayerList().getPlayers().isEmpty()) {
    ServerPlayer firstPlayer = server.getPlayerList().getPlayers().get(0);

To:

    }
}

Why? Each player needs their own spawn pin created.

Dimension Handling: What to Display

Question 1: Pin Listing - All Dimensions or Current Only?

Option A: Show only current dimension

Your pins:

Data Structure: O(1) Access

You're absolutely right about hash/dictionary access. Let me clarify:

In Java, HashMap IS the equivalent of JavaScript objects for O(1) lookup:

javascript
// JavaScript
playerPins[uuid][dimension][pinName]
java
// Java HashMap - also O(1)
playerPins.get(uuid).get(dimension).get(pinName)

So our structure should be:

java
Map<String, Map<String, Map<String, PinLocation>>> playerPins

Breaking it down:

  • Level 1: Map<String, ...> - Key = player UUID
  • Level 2: Map<String, ...> - Key = dimension name
  • Level 3: Map<String, PinLocation> - Key = pin name

Access pattern:

java
playerPins.get(playerUuid).get("minecraft:overworld").get("base")
```

Three hash lookups = O(1) + O(1) + O(1) = O(1) total. Perfect.
```

```
## Navigation Behavior

### Same Dimension Navigation

When navigating to pin in same dimension:
- Calculate angle between player position and pin position
- Calculate distance
- Display arrow pointing toward pin
- Display pin name after arrow

**Distance-based arrow:**
- `< 1 block`: `` (filled circle - arrived)
- `< 5 blocks`: `` (empty circle - very close)
- `>= 5 blocks`: Directional arrow ()

### Different Dimension Navigation

When navigating to pin in different dimension:
- Show `` (cross circle) instead of directional arrow
- Show dimension name in brackets: `[Nether]`, `[End]`, `[Overworld]`
- When player enters correct dimension, automatically switch to normal navigation

**Dimension display names:**
- `minecraft:overworld`  `Overworld`
- `minecraft:the_nether`  `Nether`
- `minecraft:the_end`  `End`

---

## Heading Compass

Shows cardinal direction player is currently facing (independent of navigation).

**8-direction compass:**
- 0  22.5 = `N `
- 45  22.5 = `NE`
- 90  22.5 = `E `
- 135  22.5 = `SE`
- 180  22.5 = `S `
- 225  22.5 = `SW`
- 270  22.5 = `W `
- 315  22.5 = `NW`

Note the space padding on single-letter directions to maintain fixed width.

---

## Time Countdown

Shows countdown to next Minecraft time event.

**Event priority (show whichever is soonest):**
1. **Bed** - Can sleep (nighttime starts at tick 12541)
2. **Mobs** - Hostile mob spawning (nighttime)
3. **Dawn** - Sunrise (daytime starts at tick 23458)

**Display format:**
- Minutes:Seconds remaining
- Event name (Bed, Mobs, Dawn)
- Example: `04:32 Bed` means 4 minutes 32 seconds until can sleep

**Minecraft time:**
- 24000 ticks per day cycle
- 1000 ticks per minute
- 20 ticks per second
- Noon = 6000
- Sunset = 12000
- Midnight = 18000
- Sunrise = 0/24000
```

package com.pidinit;

import net.fabricmc.api.ModInitializer;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerTickEvents;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerEntityEvents;
import net.minecraft.network.chat.Component;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerLevel;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerPlayer;
import net.minecraft.world.entity.EntityType;
import net.minecraft.core.BlockPos;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public class Hud implements ModInitializer {
    public static final String MOD_ID = "hud";
    public static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MOD_ID);

    private int tickCounter = 0;

    @Override
    public void onInitialize() {
        LOGGER.info("HUD mod initializing...");

        ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register(server -> {
            tickCounter++;

            if (tickCounter >= 10) {
                tickCounter = 0;

                for (ServerPlayer player : server.getPlayerList().getPlayers()) {
                    ServerLevel level = player.level();
                    BlockPos spawnPos = level.getLevelData().getRespawnData().pos();
                    double deltaX = spawnPos.getX() - player.getX();
                    double deltaZ = spawnPos.getZ() - player.getZ();
                    double angleToSpawn = Math.toDegrees(Math.atan2(deltaX, deltaZ));
                    float playerYaw = player.getYRot();
                    double relativeAngle = angleToSpawn - playerYaw;

                    while (relativeAngle > 180)
                        relativeAngle -= 360;
                    while (relativeAngle < -180)
                        relativeAngle += 360;

                    double distanceToSpawn = Math.sqrt(deltaX * deltaX + deltaZ * deltaZ);

                    String arrow;
                    if (distanceToSpawn < 1.0) {
                        arrow = "";
                    } else if (distanceToSpawn < 5.0) {
                        arrow = "";
                    } else {
                        arrow = getDirectionalArrow(relativeAngle);
                    }

                    String message = String.format("%s X: %d Y: %d H: %d",
                            arrow,
                            spawnPos.getX(),
                            spawnPos.getZ(),
                            spawnPos.getY());

                    player.displayClientMessage(Component.literal(message), true);
                }
            }
        });

        ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {
            if (entity.getType() == EntityType.WARDEN) {
                entity.discard();
                LOGGER.info("Prevented warden spawn at {}", entity.blockPosition());
            }
        });

        LOGGER.info("HUD mod initialized!");
    }

    private String getDirectionalArrow(double angle) {
        double normalizedAngle = ((angle % 360) + 360) % 360;

        if (normalizedAngle >= 337.5 || normalizedAngle < 22.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 22.5 && normalizedAngle < 67.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 67.5 && normalizedAngle < 112.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 112.5 && normalizedAngle < 157.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 157.5 && normalizedAngle < 202.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 202.5 && normalizedAngle < 247.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 247.5 && normalizedAngle < 292.5)
            return "";
        return "";
    }
}

Step 1: Add Heading Compass

We're going to add a compass showing which direction the player is facing, then put the spawn arrow to the right of it.

Understanding Player Rotation

The player's yRot (yaw rotation) tells us which direction they're facing:

  • 0 = South
  • 90 = West
  • 180 = North
  • 270 = East

We need to convert this to 8 cardinal directions (N, NE, E, SE, S, SW, W, NW).

Implementation

Step 1.1: Create the heading compass function

Add this new method to your class, right after getDirectionalArrow:

java
private String getCardinalDirection(float yaw) {
    double normalizedYaw = ((yaw % 360) + 360) % 360;
    
    if (normalizedYaw >= 337.5 || normalizedYaw < 22.5) return "S ";
    if (normalizedYaw >= 22.5 && normalizedYaw < 67.5) return "SW";
    if (normalizedYaw >= 67.5 && normalizedYaw < 112.5) return "W ";
    if (normalizedYaw >= 112.5 && normalizedYaw < 157.5) return "NW";
    if (normalizedYaw >= 157.5 && normalizedYaw < 202.5) return "N ";
    if (normalizedYaw >= 202.5 && normalizedYaw < 247.5) return "NE";
    if (normalizedYaw >= 247.5 && normalizedYaw < 292.5) return "E ";
    return "SE";
}

Why the space after single letters? Fixed width. "N " and "NW" both take 2 characters, so the layout doesn't shift when you turn.

Step 1.2: Update arrows to bold versions

Modify your getDirectionalArrow method to use bold arrows:

package net.minecraft.world.level.storage;

import com.mojang.serialization.Codec;
import com.mojang.serialization.MapCodec;
import com.mojang.serialization.codecs.RecordCodecBuilder;
import io.netty.buffer.ByteBuf;
import java.util.Locale;
import net.minecraft.CrashReportCategory;
import net.minecraft.CrashReportDetail;
import net.minecraft.core.BlockPos;
import net.minecraft.core.GlobalPos;
import net.minecraft.network.codec.ByteBufCodecs;
import net.minecraft.network.codec.StreamCodec;
import net.minecraft.resources.ResourceKey;
import net.minecraft.util.Mth;
import net.minecraft.world.Difficulty;
import net.minecraft.world.level.Level;
import net.minecraft.world.level.LevelHeightAccessor;

public interface LevelData {
    LevelData.RespawnData getRespawnData();

    long getGameTime();

    long getDayTime();

    boolean isThundering();

    boolean isRaining();

    void setRaining(boolean bl);

    boolean isHardcore();

    Difficulty getDifficulty();

    boolean isDifficultyLocked();

    default void fillCrashReportCategory(CrashReportCategory crashReportCategory, LevelHeightAccessor levelHeightAccessor) {
        crashReportCategory.setDetail(
            "Level spawn location", (CrashReportDetail<String>)(() -> CrashReportCategory.formatLocation(levelHeightAccessor, this.getRespawnData().pos()))
        );
        crashReportCategory.setDetail(
            "Level time", (CrashReportDetail<String>)(() -> String.format(Locale.ROOT, "%d game time, %d day time", this.getGameTime(), this.getDayTime()))
        );
    }

    public record RespawnData(GlobalPos globalPos, float yaw, float pitch) {
        public static final LevelData.RespawnData DEFAULT = new LevelData.RespawnData(GlobalPos.of(Level.OVERWORLD, BlockPos.ZERO), 0.0F, 0.0F);
        public static final MapCodec<LevelData.RespawnData> MAP_CODEC = RecordCodecBuilder.mapCodec(
            instance -> instance.group(
                    GlobalPos.MAP_CODEC.forGetter(LevelData.RespawnData::globalPos),
                    Codec.floatRange(-180.0F, 180.0F).fieldOf("yaw").forGetter(LevelData.RespawnData::yaw),
                    Codec.floatRange(-90.0F, 90.0F).fieldOf("pitch").forGetter(LevelData.RespawnData::pitch)
                )
                .apply(instance, LevelData.RespawnData::new)
        );
        public static final Codec<LevelData.RespawnData> CODEC = MAP_CODEC.codec();
        public static final StreamCodec<ByteBuf, LevelData.RespawnData> STREAM_CODEC = StreamCodec.composite(
            GlobalPos.STREAM_CODEC,
            LevelData.RespawnData::globalPos,
            ByteBufCodecs.FLOAT,
            LevelData.RespawnData::yaw,
            ByteBufCodecs.FLOAT,
            LevelData.RespawnData::pitch,
            LevelData.RespawnData::new
        );

        public static LevelData.RespawnData of(ResourceKey<Level> resourceKey, BlockPos blockPos, float f, float g) {
            return new LevelData.RespawnData(GlobalPos.of(resourceKey, blockPos.immutable()), Mth.wrapDegrees(f), Mth.clamp(g, -90.0F, 90.0F));
        }

        public ResourceKey<Level> dimension() {
            return this.globalPos.dimension();
        }

        public BlockPos pos() {
            return this.globalPos.pos();
        }
    }

public class SetWorldSpawnCommand {
    public static void register(CommandDispatcher<CommandSourceStack> commandDispatcher) {
        commandDispatcher.register(
            Commands.literal("setworldspawn")
                .requires(Commands.hasPermission(Commands.LEVEL_GAMEMASTERS))
                .executes(
                    commandContext -> setSpawn(commandContext.getSource(), BlockPos.containing(commandContext.getSource().getPosition()), WorldCoordinates.ZERO_ROTATION)
                )
                .then(
                    Commands.argument("pos", BlockPosArgument.blockPos())
                        .executes(commandContext -> setSpawn(commandContext.getSource(), BlockPosArgument.getSpawnablePos(commandContext, "pos"), WorldCoordinates.ZERO_ROTATION))
                        .then(
                            Commands.argument("rotation", RotationArgument.rotation())
                                .executes(
                                    commandContext -> setSpawn(
                                        commandContext.getSource(), BlockPosArgument.getSpawnablePos(commandContext, "pos"), RotationArgument.getRotation(commandContext, "rotation")
                                    )
                                )
                        )
                )
        );
    }

    private static int setSpawn(CommandSourceStack commandSourceStack, BlockPos blockPos, Coordinates coordinates) {
        ServerLevel serverLevel = commandSourceStack.getLevel();
        Vec2 vec2 = coordinates.getRotation(commandSourceStack);
        float f = vec2.y;
        float g = vec2.x;
        LevelData.RespawnData respawnData = LevelData.RespawnData.of(serverLevel.dimension(), blockPos, f, g);
        serverLevel.setRespawnData(respawnData);
        commandSourceStack.sendSuccess(
            () -> Component.translatable(
                "commands.setworldspawn.success",
                blockPos.getX(),
                blockPos.getY(),
                blockPos.getZ(),
                respawnData.yaw(),
                respawnData.pitch(),
                serverLevel.dimension().identifier().toString()
            ),
            true
        );
        return 1;
    }

package com.pidinit;

import net.fabricmc.api.ModInitializer;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerTickEvents;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerEntityEvents;
import net.minecraft.network.chat.Component;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerLevel;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerPlayer;
import net.minecraft.world.entity.EntityType;
import net.minecraft.core.BlockPos;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public class Hud implements ModInitializer {
    public static final String MOD_ID = "hud";
    public static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MOD_ID);

    private int tickCounter = 0;

    @Override
    public void onInitialize() {
        LOGGER.info("HUD mod initializing...");

        ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register(server -> {
            tickCounter++;

            if (tickCounter >= 10) {

                tickCounter = 0;

                for (ServerPlayer player : server.getPlayerList().getPlayers()) {
                    ServerLevel level = player.level();

                    float playerYaw = player.getYRot();

                    while (relativeAngle > 180)
                        relativeAngle -= 360;
                    while (relativeAngle < -180)
                        relativeAngle += 360;

                    double distanceToSpawn = Math.sqrt(deltaX * deltaX + deltaZ * deltaZ);

                    String arrow;
                    if (distanceToSpawn < 1.0) {
                        arrow = "";
                    } else if (distanceToSpawn < 5.0) {
                        arrow = "";
                    } else {
                        arrow = getDirectionalArrow(relativeAngle);
                    }

                    String heading = getCardinalDirection(playerYaw);

                    String message = String.format("%s  %s spawn X:%d Y:%d H:%d",
                            heading,
                            arrow,
                            spawnPos.getX(),
                            spawnPos.getZ(),
                            spawnPos.getY());

                    player.displayClientMessage(Component.literal(message), true);
                }
            }
        });

        ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {
            if (entity.getType() == EntityType.WARDEN) {
                entity.discard();
                LOGGER.info("Prevented warden spawn at {}", entity.blockPosition());
            }
        });

        LOGGER.info("HUD mod initialized!");
    }

    private String getDirectionalArrow(double angle) {
        double normalizedAngle = ((angle % 360) + 360) % 360;

        if (normalizedAngle >= 337.5 || normalizedAngle < 22.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 22.5 && normalizedAngle < 67.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 67.5 && normalizedAngle < 112.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 112.5 && normalizedAngle < 157.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 157.5 && normalizedAngle < 202.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 202.5 && normalizedAngle < 247.5)
            return "";
        if (normalizedAngle >= 247.5 && normalizedAngle < 292.5)
            return "";
        return "";
    }

    private String getCardinalDirection(float yaw) {
        double normalizedYaw = ((yaw % 360) + 360) % 360;

        if (normalizedYaw >= 337.5 || normalizedYaw < 22.5)
            return "S ";
        if (normalizedYaw >= 22.5 && normalizedYaw < 67.5)
            return "SW";
        if (normalizedYaw >= 67.5 && normalizedYaw < 112.5)
            return "W ";
        if (normalizedYaw >= 112.5 && normalizedYaw < 157.5)
            return "NW";
        if (normalizedYaw >= 157.5 && normalizedYaw < 202.5)
            return "N ";
        if (normalizedYaw >= 202.5 && normalizedYaw < 247.5)
            return "NE";
        if (normalizedYaw >= 247.5 && normalizedYaw < 292.5)
            return "E ";
        return "SE";
    }

package com.pidinit;

import net.fabricmc.api.ModInitializer;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerTickEvents;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerEntityEvents;
import net.minecraft.network.chat.Component;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerLevel;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerPlayer;
import net.minecraft.world.entity.EntityType;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public class Hud implements ModInitializer {
	public static final String MOD_ID = "hud";
	public static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MOD_ID);

	private int tickCounter = 0;

	@Override
	public void onInitialize() {
		LOGGER.info("HUD mod initializing...");

		ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register(server -> {
			tickCounter++;

			if (tickCounter >= 10) {
				tickCounter = 0;

				for (ServerPlayer player : server.getPlayerList().getPlayers()) {
					int x = (int) player.getX();
					int z = (int) player.getZ();
					int y = (int) player.getY();
					
					String heading = getCardinalDirection(player.getYRot());

					String message = String.format("X:%7d Y:%7d H:%4d  %s", x, z, y, heading);

					player.displayClientMessage(Component.literal(message), true);
				}
			}
		});

		ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {
			if (entity.getType() == EntityType.WARDEN) {
				entity.discard();
				LOGGER.info("Prevented warden spawn at {}", entity.blockPosition());
			}
		});

		LOGGER.info("HUD mod initialized!");
	}

	private String getCardinalDirection(float yaw) {
		double normalizedYaw = ((yaw % 360) + 360) % 360;

		if (normalizedYaw >= 337.5 || normalizedYaw < 22.5)
			return "S ";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 22.5 && normalizedYaw < 67.5)
			return "SW";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 67.5 && normalizedYaw < 112.5)
			return "W ";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 112.5 && normalizedYaw < 157.5)
			return "NW";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 157.5 && normalizedYaw < 202.5)
			return "N ";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 202.5 && normalizedYaw < 247.5)
			return "NE";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 247.5 && normalizedYaw < 292.5)
			return "E ";
		return "SE";
	}
}

Perfect! I found the exact information. Let me search for hostile mob spawning specifics:

Research Summary

Based on the official Minecraft Wiki, here are the exact timings for Minecraft 1.21.1:

Day/Night Cycle (24000 ticks = 20 minutes)

  • Day: 0 to 12000 ticks (10 minutes)
  • Sunset: 12000 to 13000 ticks (50 seconds)
  • Night: 13000 to 23000 ticks (7 minutes, 6.7 seconds)
  • Sunrise: 23000 to 24000 (wraps to 0) (50 seconds)

Bed Sleep Available

  • Clear weather: tick 12542 to 23459
  • Rainy weather: tick 12010 to 23991
  • Thunderstorm: anytime

Hostile Mob Spawning

  • Hostile mobs can spawn for 13188 ticks during night
  • This is the duration when sky light level is low enough

Implementation Plan

Data Structure

We need to track three events and show whichever is soonest:

  1. Bed - when player can sleep (tick 12542)
  2. Mobs - when hostile mobs start spawning (tick 13000)
  3. Dawn - when day starts (tick 23000 wraps to 0)

Algorithm

1. Get current day time: level.getDayTime() % 24000
2. Calculate ticks until each event
3. Pick the soonest event
4. Convert ticks to MM:SS format
5. Display with event name

Line-by-Line Implementation

Step 1: Get current time in the day cycle

java
long dayTime = level.getDayTime() % 24000;

getDayTime() returns total ticks since world creation. We use modulo 24000 to get position in current day (0-23999).

Step 2: Calculate ticks until bed time (12542)

java
long ticksUntilBed = (12542 - dayTime + 24000) % 24000;

If current time is 10000, bed is in 2542 ticks.
If current time is 15000, bed is in (12542 - 15000 + 24000) % 24000 = 21542 ticks (tomorrow).

Step 3: Calculate ticks until mobs (13000)

java
long ticksUntilMobs = (13000 - dayTime + 24000) % 24000;

Same logic as bed.

Step 4: Calculate ticks until dawn (0)

java
long ticksUntilDawn = (24000 - dayTime) % 24000;

If current time is 15000, dawn in 9000 ticks.
If current time is 100, dawn in 23900 ticks.

Step 5: Find soonest event

java
String event;
long ticksUntil;

if (ticksUntilBed <= ticksUntilMobs && ticksUntilBed <= ticksUntilDawn) {
    event = "Bed ";
    ticksUntil = ticksUntilBed;
} else if (ticksUntilMobs <= ticksUntilDawn) {
    event = "Mobs";
    ticksUntil = ticksUntilMobs;
} else {
    event = "Dawn";
    ticksUntil = ticksUntilDawn;
}

Step 6: Convert ticks to minutes:seconds

java
int minutes = (int) (ticksUntil / 1200);
int seconds = (int) ((ticksUntil % 1200) / 20);

1200 ticks = 1 minute (60 seconds 20 ticks/second).
Remaining ticks 20 = seconds.

Step 7: Format time string

java
String timeString = String.format("%02d:%02d", minutes, seconds);

%02d means 2 digits, zero-padded. Example: 04:32

Step 8: Update message format

java
String message = String.format("X:%-7d Y:%-7d H:%-4d  %-2s  %s in %s", 
    x, z, y, heading, event, timeString);

Output: X:246 Y:-154 H:114 NW Bed in 04:32

Full Implementation

java
package com.pidinit;

import net.fabricmc.api.ModInitializer;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerTickEvents;
import net.fabricmc.fabric.api.event.lifecycle.v1.ServerEntityEvents;
import net.minecraft.network.chat.Component;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerLevel;
import net.minecraft.server.level.ServerPlayer;
import net.minecraft.world.entity.EntityType;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public class Hud implements ModInitializer {
	public static final String MOD_ID = "hud";
	public static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MOD_ID);

	private int tickCounter = 0;

	@Override
	public void onInitialize() {
		LOGGER.info("HUD mod initializing...");

		ServerTickEvents.END_SERVER_TICK.register(server -> {
			tickCounter++;

			if (tickCounter >= 10) {
				tickCounter = 0;

				for (ServerPlayer player : server.getPlayerList().getPlayers()) {
					ServerLevel level = player.level();
					
					int x = (int) player.getX();
					int z = (int) player.getZ();
					int y = (int) player.getY();
					
					String heading = getCardinalDirection(player.getYRot());
					
					long dayTime = level.getDayTime() % 24000;
					
					long ticksUntilBed = (12542 - dayTime + 24000) % 24000;
					long ticksUntilMobs = (13000 - dayTime + 24000) % 24000;
					long ticksUntilDawn = (24000 - dayTime) % 24000;
					
					String event;
					long ticksUntil;
					
					if (ticksUntilBed <= ticksUntilMobs && ticksUntilBed <= ticksUntilDawn) {
						event = "Bed ";
						ticksUntil = ticksUntilBed;
					} else if (ticksUntilMobs <= ticksUntilDawn) {
						event = "Mobs";
						ticksUntil = ticksUntilMobs;
					} else {
						event = "Dawn";
						ticksUntil = ticksUntilDawn;
					}
					
					int minutes = (int) (ticksUntil / 1200);
					int seconds = (int) ((ticksUntil % 1200) / 20);
					String timeString = String.format("%02d:%02d", minutes, seconds);

					String message = String.format("X:%-7d Y:%-7d H:%-4d  %-2s  %s in %s", 
							x, z, y, heading, event, timeString);

					player.displayClientMessage(Component.literal(message), true);
				}
			}
		});

		ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {
			if (entity.getType() == EntityType.WARDEN) {
				entity.discard();
				LOGGER.info("Prevented warden spawn at {}", entity.blockPosition());
			}
		});

		LOGGER.info("HUD mod initialized!");
	}

	private String getCardinalDirection(float yaw) {
		double normalizedYaw = ((yaw % 360) + 360) % 360;

		if (normalizedYaw >= 337.5 || normalizedYaw < 22.5)
			return "S ";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 22.5 && normalizedYaw < 67.5)
			return "SW";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 67.5 && normalizedYaw < 112.5)
			return "W ";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 112.5 && normalizedYaw < 157.5)
			return "NW";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 157.5 && normalizedYaw < 202.5)
			return "N ";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 202.5 && normalizedYaw < 247.5)
			return "NE";
		if (normalizedYaw >= 247.5 && normalizedYaw < 292.5)
			return "E ";
		return "SE";
	}
}

This implementation:

  • Shows accurate countdown to next game event
  • Handles all edge cases (time wrapping at midnight)
  • Uses official Minecraft tick values from the wiki
  • Works in Overworld normal weather only (as specified)
  • Updates every 10 ticks (twice per second)

Here's the color system implementation:

java
private enum Color {
	GREY("7"),
	GOLD("6"),
	BLUE("9"),
	GREEN("a"),
	WHITE("f"),
	RED("c"),
	RESET("r");
	
	private final String code;
	
	Color(String code) {
		this.code = code;
	}
	
	public String apply(String text) {
		return this.code + text + RESET.code;
	}
}

private String bold(String text) {
	return "l" + text + "r";
}

Example usage in your message format:

java
String message = String.format("%s%s%-7d %s%s%-7d %s%s%-4d  %s  %s in %s",
		Color.GOLD.apply("X:"),
		Color.GREY.apply(String.valueOf(x)),
		"",
		Color.GOLD.apply("Y:"),
		Color.GREY.apply(String.valueOf(z)),
		"",
		Color.GOLD.apply("H:"),
		Color.GREY.apply(String.valueOf(y)),
		"",
		Color.BLUE.apply(bold(heading)),
		event,
		timeString);

Wait, that's messy with the padding. Let me fix it:

java
String xCoord = Color.GOLD.apply("X:") + Color.GREY.apply(String.format("%-7d", x));
String yCoord = Color.GOLD.apply("Y:") + Color.GREY.apply(String.format("%-7d", z));
String hCoord = Color.GOLD.apply("H:") + Color.GREY.apply(String.format("%-4d", y));
String formattedHeading = Color.BLUE.apply(bold(heading));

String message = String.format("%s %s %s  %s  %s in %s",
		xCoord, yCoord, hCoord, formattedHeading, event, timeString);

How Minecraft color codes work:

  • is the formatting character
  • Letter/number after defines the format
  • r resets all formatting
  • l makes text bold
  • Colors: 7 grey, 6 gold, 9 blue, a green, f white, c red

The Color.RESET at the end of each apply() ensures colors don't bleed into subsequent text.

private enum Color {
	GREY("7"),
	GOLD("6"),
	BLUE("9"),
	GREEN("a"),
	WHITE("f"),
	RED("c");
	
	private final String code;
	
	Color(String code) {
		this.code = code;
	}

private String color(String text, Color color) {
	return color.code + text + "r";
}

private String bold(String text) {
	return "l" + text + "r";
}

**Breaking this down line by line:**

`dispatcher.register(...)` - Tell Minecraft "here's a new command"

`Commands.literal("pin")` - The command starts with `/pin` (literal text)

`.then(Commands.argument("name", MessageArgument.message()))` - After `/pin`, expect an argument called "name" that captures everything after it (handles spaces)

`.executes(this::executePin)` - When someone types `/pin <name>`, call the `executePin` method

`.then(Commands.literal("--force"))` - Optionally, they can add `--force` after the name

`.executes(this::executePinForce)` - If they include `--force`, call `executePinForce` instead

**The command tree looks like:**

/pin
   <name>   executes executePin()

Part 5: Implement executePin (without --force)

Add this method to your class:

java
private int executePin(CommandContext<CommandSourceStack> context) {
    try {
        ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
        String pinName = MessageArgument.getMessage(context, "name").getString();
        
        if (pins.containsKey(pinName)) {
            BlockPos existingPin = pins.get(pinName);
            BlockPos currentPos = player.blockPosition();
            
            player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
                color("Pin '" + pinName + "' already exists at ", Color.GOLD) +
                color("X:" + existingPin.getX() + " Y:" + existingPin.getZ() + " H:" + existingPin.getY(), Color.GREY)
            ));
            player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
                color("Current location: ", Color.GOLD) +
                color("X:" + currentPos.getX() + " Y:" + currentPos.getZ() + " H:" + currentPos.getY(), Color.GREY)
            ));
            player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
                color("Use '/pin " + pinName + " --force' to overwrite", Color.GOLD)
            ));
            return 0;
        }
        
        BlockPos pos = player.blockPosition();
        pins.put(pinName, pos);
        
        String dimensionName = getDimensionName(player.level());
        player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
            color("Pin '" + pinName + "' created at ", Color.GREEN) +
            color("X:" + pos.getX() + " Y:" + pos.getZ() + " H:" + pos.getY(), Color.GREY) +
            color(" [" + dimensionName + "]", Color.BLUE)
        ));
        
        return 1;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        LOGGER.error("Error executing pin command", e);
        return 0;
    }
}

Line-by-line explanation:

ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
Get who ran the command. Throws exception if run from console.

String pinName = MessageArgument.getMessage(context, "name").getString();
Extract the pin name they typed.

if (pins.containsKey(pinName)) Check if this pin name already exists.

If exists: Show them the existing location, their current location, and tell them how to use --force.

return 0; - Command failed (pin not created)

If doesn't exist: pins.put(pinName, pos); - Save the pin

player.sendSystemMessage(...) - Send confirmation message to player

return 1; - Command succeeded

Part 6: Implement executePinForce (with --force)

java
private int executePinForce(CommandContext<CommandSourceStack> context) {
    try {
        ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
        String pinName = MessageArgument.getMessage(context, "name").getString();
        
        BlockPos pos = player.blockPosition();
        pins.put(pinName, pos);
        
        String dimensionName = getDimensionName(player.level());
        player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
            color("Pin '" + pinName + "' updated at ", Color.GREEN) +
            color("X:" + pos.getX() + " Y:" + pos.getZ() + " H:" + pos.getY(), Color.GREY) +
            color(" [" + dimensionName + "]", Color.BLUE)
        ));
        
        return 1;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        LOGGER.error("Error executing pin force command", e);
        return 0;
    }
}

This is simpler - it doesn't check if the pin exists. It just overwrites it unconditionally.

Part 7: Helper Method - Get Dimension Name

java
private String getDimensionName(ServerLevel level) {
    String dimension = level.dimension().toString();
    if (dimension.contains("overworld")) return "Overworld";
    if (dimension.contains("the_nether")) return "Nether";
    if (dimension.contains("the_end")) return "End";
    return dimension;
}

This converts ResourceKey[minecraft:dimension / minecraft:overworld] to just "Overworld".

                color("Pin '" + pinName + "' already exists at X:" + existingPin.getX() + " Y:" + existingPin.getZ() + " H:" + existingPin.getY(), Color.GOLD)
            ));
            player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
                color("Current location: X:" + currentPos.getX() + " Y:" + currentPos.getZ() + " H:" + currentPos.getY(), Color.GREY)
            ));
            player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
                color("Use '/pin " + pinName + " --force' to overwrite", Color.GOLD)
            ));
            return 0;
        }
        
        BlockPos pos = player.blockPosition();
        pins.put(pinName, pos);
        
        String dimensionName = getDimensionName(player.level());
        player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
            color("Pin '" + pinName + "' created at X:" + pos.getX() + " Y:" + pos.getZ() + " H:" + pos.getY() + " [" + dimensionName + "]", Color.GREEN)
        ));
        
        return 1;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        LOGGER.error("Error executing pin command", e);
        return 0;
    }
}

java
private int executePinForce(CommandContext<CommandSourceStack> context) {
    try {
        ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
        String pinName = MessageArgument.getMessage(context, "name").getString();
        
        BlockPos pos = player.blockPosition();
        pins.put(pinName, pos);
        
        String dimensionName = getDimensionName(player.level());
        player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal(
            color("Pin '" + pinName + "' updated at X:" + pos.getX() + " Y:" + pos.getZ() + " H:" + pos.getY() + " [" + dimensionName + "]", Color.GREEN)
        ));
        
        return 1;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        LOGGER.error("Error executing pin force command", e);
        return 0;
    }
}

Understanding .then() in Brigadier

Brigadier builds command trees. Think of it like this: 

/pin                           literal node
     <name>                argument node
          executes()       execution handler

Without arguments:

java
Commands.literal("pin").executes(context -> {...})

This creates: /pin (executes immediately when typed)

With arguments:

java
Commands.literal("pin")
    .then(Commands.argument("name", StringArgumentType.greedyString())
        .executes(context -> {...})
    )

This creates: /pin <name> (executes only after providing the name)

The .then() method:

  • Adds a child node to the command tree
  • Can chain multiple arguments or subcommands
  • Each .then() adds another level to the tree

Example of multiple levels:

java
Commands.literal("pin")
    .then(Commands.argument("name", StringArgumentType.greedyString())
        .then(Commands.literal("--force")
            .executes(context -> {...})  // /pin <name> --force
        )
        .executes(context -> {...})      // /pin <name>
    )

This creates two possible commands:

  • /pin my base
  • /pin my base --force

package net.minecraft.resources;

import com.google.common.collect.MapMaker;
import com.mojang.serialization.Codec;
import io.netty.buffer.ByteBuf;
import java.util.Optional;
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentMap;
import net.minecraft.core.Registry;
import net.minecraft.core.registries.Registries;
import net.minecraft.network.codec.StreamCodec;

public class ResourceKey<T> {
    private static final ConcurrentMap<ResourceKey.InternKey, ResourceKey<?>> VALUES = new MapMaker().weakValues().makeMap();
    private final Identifier registryName;
    private final Identifier identifier;

    public static <T> Codec<ResourceKey<T>> codec(ResourceKey<? extends Registry<T>> resourceKey) {
        return Identifier.CODEC.xmap(identifier -> create(resourceKey, identifier), ResourceKey::identifier);
    }

    public static <T> StreamCodec<ByteBuf, ResourceKey<T>> streamCodec(ResourceKey<? extends Registry<T>> resourceKey) {
        return Identifier.STREAM_CODEC.map(identifier -> create(resourceKey, identifier), ResourceKey::identifier);
    }

    public static <T> ResourceKey<T> create(ResourceKey<? extends Registry<T>> resourceKey, Identifier identifier) {
        return create(resourceKey.identifier, identifier);
    }

    public static <T> ResourceKey<Registry<T>> createRegistryKey(Identifier identifier) {
        return create(Registries.ROOT_REGISTRY_NAME, identifier);
    }

    private static <T> ResourceKey<T> create(Identifier identifier, Identifier identifier2) {
        return (ResourceKey<T>)VALUES.computeIfAbsent(
            new ResourceKey.InternKey(identifier, identifier2), internKey -> new ResourceKey(internKey.registry, internKey.identifier)
        );
    }

    private ResourceKey(Identifier identifier, Identifier identifier2) {
        this.registryName = identifier;
        this.identifier = identifier2;
    }

    public String toString() {
        return "ResourceKey[" + this.registryName + " / " + this.identifier + "]";
    }

    public boolean isFor(ResourceKey<? extends Registry<?>> resourceKey) {
        return this.registryName.equals(resourceKey.identifier());
    }

    public <E> Optional<ResourceKey<E>> cast(ResourceKey<? extends Registry<E>> resourceKey) {
        return this.isFor(resourceKey) ? Optional.of(this) : Optional.empty();
    }

    public Identifier identifier() {
        return this.identifier;
    }

    public Identifier registry() {
        return this.registryName;
    }

    public ResourceKey<Registry<T>> registryKey() {
        return createRegistryKey(this.registryName);
    }

    record InternKey(Identifier registry, Identifier identifier) {
    }
}

Next Step: Store Pins in Memory

We'll create a nested Map structure to hold pins per player, per dimension:

  • Level 1: Player UUID Level 2
  • Level 2: Dimension name Level 3
  • Level 3: Pin name Position data

This lets us do instant lookups like: pins.get(playerUUID).get(dimension).get(pinName)

Add these fields at the top of your Hud class (right after private int tickCounter = 0;):

java
private static class PinData {
    final int x, y, z;
    final String dimension;
    
    PinData(int x, int y, int z, String dimension) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
        this.z = z;
        this.dimension = dimension;
    }
}

private final Map<String, Map<String, Map<String, PinData>>> pins = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

Now update your /pin command to actually store the pin:

java
CommandRegistrationCallback.EVENT.register((dispatcher, registryAccess, environment) -> {
    dispatcher.register(
        Commands.literal("pin")
            .then(Commands.argument("name", StringArgumentType.greedyString())
                .executes(context -> {
                    String pinName = StringArgumentType.getString(context, "name");
                    
                    ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
                    BlockPos pos = player.blockPosition();
                    String dimension = player.level().dimension().identifier().toString();
                    String playerUUID = player.getStringUUID();
                    
                    pins.computeIfAbsent(playerUUID, k -> new ConcurrentHashMap<>())
                        .computeIfAbsent(dimension, k -> new ConcurrentHashMap<>())
                        .put(pinName, new PinData(pos.getX(), pos.getY(), pos.getZ(), dimension));
                    
                    context.getSource().sendSystemMessage(
                        Component.literal(String.format(" Pin '%s' saved at X:%d Y:%d Z:%d", 
                            pinName, pos.getX(), pos.getY(), pos.getZ()))
                    );
                    return 1;
                })
            )
    );
});

You're absolutely right. Let's add a /pins command to list all pins before testing.

Replace your existing /pins command (the one that just says "Pin system works!") with this:

java
CommandRegistrationCallback.EVENT.register((dispatcher, registryAccess, environment) -> {
    dispatcher.register(
        Commands.literal("pins").executes(context -> {
            ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
            String playerUUID = player.getStringUUID();
            String currentDimension = player.level().dimension().identifier().toString();
            
            Map<String, Map<String, PinData>> playerPins = pins.get(playerUUID);
            
            if (playerPins == null || !playerPins.containsKey(currentDimension)) {
                context.getSource().sendSystemMessage(
                    Component.literal("No pins in this dimension")
                );
                return 1;
            }
            
            Map<String, PinData> dimensionPins = playerPins.get(currentDimension);
            
            if (dimensionPins.isEmpty()) {
                context.getSource().sendSystemMessage(
                    Component.literal("No pins in this dimension")
                );
                return 1;
            }
            
            context.getSource().sendSystemMessage(
                Component.literal("=== Your Pins ===")
            );
            
            for (Map.Entry<String, PinData> entry : dimensionPins.entrySet()) {
                PinData pin = entry.getValue();
                context.getSource().sendSystemMessage(
                    Component.literal(String.format("  %s: X:%d Y:%d Z:%d", 
                        entry.getKey(), pin.x, pin.y, pin.z))
                );
            }
            
            return 1;
        })
    );
});

Great! Now let's add file persistence so pins survive server restarts.

Next Step: Save Pins to JSON Files

We'll save each player's pins to a separate JSON file: world/data/pins/<player-uuid>.json

The JSON structure will be:

json
{
  "minecraft:overworld": {
    "base": {"x": 100, "y": 64, "z": 200, "dimension": "minecraft:overworld"},
    "farm": {"x": 150, "y": 70, "z": 250, "dimension": "minecraft:overworld"}
  },
  "minecraft:nether": {
    "portal": {"x": 12, "y": 64, "z": 25, "dimension": "minecraft:nether"}
  }
}

We'll use Gson (already included in Minecraft) to handle JSON serialization.

Add these imports at the top:

java
import com.google.gson.Gson;
import com.google.gson.GsonBuilder;
import com.google.gson.reflect.TypeToken;
import java.io.File;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.lang.reflect.Type;
import java.nio.file.Path;

Add these helper methods to your Hud class (after the bold() method):

java
private Path getPinsDirectory(ServerLevel level) {
    return level.getServer().getServerDirectory().toPath().resolve("data").resolve("pins");
}

private File getPlayerPinsFile(ServerLevel level, String playerUUID) {
    Path pinsDir = getPinsDirectory(level);
    pinsDir.toFile().mkdirs();
    return pinsDir.resolve(playerUUID + ".json").toFile();
}

private void savePins(ServerLevel level, String playerUUID) {
    Map<String, Map<String, PinData>> playerPins = pins.get(playerUUID);
    if (playerPins == null) return;
    
    File file = getPlayerPinsFile(level, playerUUID);
    Gson gson = new GsonBuilder().setPrettyPrinting().create();
    
    try (FileWriter writer = new FileWriter(file)) {
        gson.toJson(playerPins, writer);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        LOGGER.error("Failed to save pins for player {}", playerUUID, e);
    }
}

private void loadPins(ServerLevel level, String playerUUID) {
    File file = getPlayerPinsFile(level, playerUUID);
    if (!file.exists()) return;
    
    Gson gson = new Gson();
    Type type = new TypeToken<Map<String, Map<String, PinData>>>(){}.getType();
    
    try (FileReader reader = new FileReader(file)) {
        Map<String, Map<String, PinData>> loadedPins = gson.fromJson(reader, type);
        if (loadedPins != null) {
            pins.put(playerUUID, new ConcurrentHashMap<>(loadedPins));
        }
    } catch (IOException e) {
        LOGGER.error("Failed to load pins for player {}", playerUUID, e);
    }
}

Now update your /pin command to save after creating a pin. Replace the entire /pin command registration with:

java
CommandRegistrationCallback.EVENT.register((dispatcher, registryAccess, environment) -> {
    dispatcher.register(
        Commands.literal("pin")
            .then(Commands.argument("name", StringArgumentType.greedyString())
                .executes(context -> {
                    String pinName = StringArgumentType.getString(context, "name");
                    
                    ServerPlayer player = context.getSource().getPlayerOrException();
                    BlockPos pos = player.blockPosition();
                    String dimension = player.level().dimension().identifier().toString();
                    String playerUUID = player.getStringUUID();
                    
                    pins.computeIfAbsent(playerUUID, k -> new ConcurrentHashMap<>())
                        .computeIfAbsent(dimension, k -> new ConcurrentHashMap<>())
                        .put(pinName, new PinData(pos.getX(), pos.getY(), pos.getZ(), dimension));
                    
                    savePins(player.level(), playerUUID);
                    
                    context.getSource().sendSystemMessage(
                        Component.literal(String.format(" Pin '%s' saved at X:%d Y:%d Z:%d", 
                            pinName, pos.getX(), pos.getY(), pos.getZ()))
                    );
                    return 1;
                })
            )
    );
});

Add a player join event to load pins when players connect. Add this in your onInitialize() method after the warden prevention code:

java
ServerEntityEvents.ENTITY_LOAD.register((entity, world) -> {
    if (entity instanceof ServerPlayer player) {
        loadPins(player.level(), player.getStringUUID());
    }
});

Test it:

  1. Create a pin: /pin my base
  2. Check it saved: /pins
  3. Stop the server
  4. Check world/data/pins/<your-uuid>.json exists
  5. Start the server again
  6. Run /pins - your pin should still be there!
